      "content": "Apologies for the abrupt stop. Let's continue from where we left off.\n\nThe pressure difference (ΔP) between the dynamic pressure (P_dynamic) and the static pressure (P_static) can be related to the airspeed (V) using Bernoulli's equation and the following relationship derived from it:\n\nΔP = 0.5 * ρ * V^2\n\nWhere:\n- ΔP is the pressure difference (in Pascals, Pa)\n- ρ (rho) is the air density (in kilograms per cubic meter, kg/m^3)\n- V is the airspeed (in meters per second, m/s)\n\nTo convert this pressure difference into knots, which is a unit of speed commonly used in aviation, we use the following conversion factors:\n\n1 knot = 0.514444 m/s\n1 Pascal = 1 kg/(m*s^2)\n\nRearranging the equation to solve for V in knots, we get:\n\nV (knots) = sqrt((2 * ΔP) / (ρ * 0.514444^2))\n\nThis equation allows us to calculate the airspeed in knots given the pressure difference and the air density.\n\nNow, if only the pitot tube is blocked,",
